					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A enchanter guide, levels 1-16, and some good advice</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:entropy@icehex.net">Cendorie</a> | 
		            2/8/2001 5:57:21 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">This is my first attempt at a guide, so i'll do the best I can to keep it all coherent and usefull, some e-mails to entropy@icehex.net would be WONDERFUL if you find any of this usefull to you.<BR>
<BR>
**note** -- some of the info in this guide is centered around you being in Antonica -- but dark elves/elves that are staying in their own lands for a while can find this very usefull.<BR>
<BR>
1-5: Early levels...<BR>
<BR>
These are nothing really fancy.  From creation, get to your guild hall, and get your basic robe equipped.  Now go out, kill a bunch of bats/rats/snakes until you get some money from selling their drops to the various merchants.  Use this money FIRST to get all your level one spells, don't worry about fancy equipment yet.  Pick up some tiny daggers with your things, you'll need some.<BR>
<BR>
From there, you have a pet spell already!  Your animation is really good at this level, you just bonk something, stand back, throw a couple shallow breaths in there, and you'll do just fine.<BR>
<BR>
Once you hit 4, your abilities will start to SERIOSUALLY expand.  Your level four animation does a much better job, and you get a upgrade to your DoT spell, as well as quite a few usefull abilities (gate, tashan, mezmorize)..From here, you should be ready to leave the newbie zone and move out a little.<BR>
<BR>
If you happen to be near freeport, east commons is EXCELLENT for you now.  With your pet and a little common sense, you can take yellow cons with ease.  Black bears, shadow wolves, just use your pet to do the tanking for you, stand back and blast.  If the mob gets close to you, stun it with your color flux, step back, and let the pet do the fighting for you.<BR>
<BR>
One think you need to learn NOW is basic crowd control.  At level four or five, you're not going to be camping any spawns, so you're not going to have to worry about serious crowd control.  But when that bear/wolf happens to bring a guest into the frenzy, stun both of them (Color Flux is a AoE -- and is STILL in use to me at level 17), step back, mezmorize the one your pet is not attacking, and you now only have to deal with one target.  The trick to being good at this level is not to blow all your mana on DoT's -- as long as your pet is doing well, don't cast that DoT until the last one wears off, they don't stack, you're just resetting the DoT timer and wasting a bit of mana.<BR>
<BR>
You should now be around level 6 or 7, which can be a little tough at this stage.  Most even cons to you will tear you apart in melee, so taking a bunch of blue things at this level is not really a bad thing (just time consuming)..You might want to consider getting with a camping group now, the orc camps in EC will do quite well for you, just remember to keep back, mez the extras for your group (*program a hotkey, and teach those tanks to stay off your mezzed targets. Be bossy, we're enchanters, we're supossed to be!*)...Camping is a good thing at this level, and probably one of your faster bets for some good exp.<BR>
<BR>
Now, using all of this, you should be able to get level eight.  Here's where things get nice.  Your new pet fights at well as a 5th level warrior (with fewer HP), and you start to get some class defining spells.  Equipment wise, you should have enough cash now to get to work.  Basicially, you should have a full set of decent armor (patch-work, leather if you can afford it), and have enough PP left over to talk with some players and get some good things.  I recommend a good 2hblunt weapon, preferbally a magical one if you can afford it, and get to your guild hall for a robe upgrade.  Shout around for a Gossimer Robe if you want, they sell from 10-20PP (even though people will try to get a lot more for them) and have a very decent AC.  Now, back to the spells and what you should be doing with your time.<BR>
<BR>
Level Eight.  You have a pretty nice set of spells now.  Enter chaotic feedback, a 48-point damage DD, with a decent taunt factor to it.  You're going to hate this one, it's your FIRST evocation line spell, which you probably have not sunk a single practice session into.  Fix that now, I recommend putting at least 5 into it.  Now go out, find blues, and nuke away until you're getting more damage then fizzle.  You get a lot of upgrades to this spell, and you're going to need to be able to do some DD, ingore the others saying that you have no need for it, I find being able to do over 200+points of damage at level 8 with full mana pretty impressive, and good when you know you've got some downtime coming.<BR>
<BR>
Other spells you get and what to do with them:<BR>
<BR>
Root:  Use this often.  Root as your open attack, go up and bonk the target, get your pet onto it, sit back and unload that DD spell.  The root will keep your DD from taunting the mob onto you, (be prepared to color flux and recast), and your new pet will dish out some very nice damage for you.  When you're camping things (I did my first Northern Desert of Ro dervish camping thing here, at derv1, scared of Dorn B'Dinn) you'll be quite effective, and if you're learning how to use that mezmorize spell and talk well with your group, they are going to not want to camp anything without the enchanter along.  <BR>
<BR>
At level 8, you're also getting a wonderful spell.  Good news!  If you're a dark elf, you don't have to work for this.  Enchant silver.  it's time to take up Jewel-Craft, since we're the ONLY class that can do this skill without the help of another player.  We're the only ones that can enchant metal for jewel-crafting.  This is a EXPENSIVE skill, and i'm not going to take to much time on it, just this breif rundown.  Find a list off the web that shows you what can be made, and start with the easiest. I started with the cheepest stone, and worked it until my skill got to around 15..Then I was ready to try other stones, and with some hard work, was making 10plat a hour selling silver enchanted itmes to other newbies.  Help people out at this stage, give them your practice items or the ones that you can't sell or use.  If you're in this to make a profit right now, make as many INT and WIS boosting items as you can, they sell quite fast.<BR>
<BR>
Ok, enough with new skills, time for more info on how to use them and get to 12.  I didn't have too hard of a time here, but it was pretty tough.  I did well in North Ro alone hunting wandering orcs, sand scarabs, giant tarantualls, and anything that conneed even or blue to me using the tactics described above.  With a group, I was able to help quite a bit, and get some nice exp up my sleeve.<BR>
<BR>
NRO is really your best bet at this level for EXP if you are on Antonica, oasis is still too much for you, and you should have your hands full.  Watch out for Ghouls, Madmen, Mummies, and most undead in NRO, they can probably kill you fast, and are tough to control.  Stick to camping some dervish spawns, and soloing the smaller things when you don't feel like grouping.  If North Ro is not your thing at the moment, you can also do more orc camping in EC, move on to the middle EC grounds for lions and kodiaks, or even head over to the WC zone line and take some bigger things.<BR>
<BR>
12 is a pretty big level for us.  We can now bind ourselves anywhere we want to in Norrath.  This makes corpse retrievel a breeze, and also lets us bind others, for some donations or some buffs or just to be nice.  Languid Pace, use this when camping something or working with tanks, they LOVE it when you can slow down that nasty mob's attack rate, and your party will thank you for the decreased downtime for healing.  We also get the charm spell, which is a little more usefull when you get a little higher then 12, at 12, it takes almost 1/3 your mana, is pretty easy to resist, and will get you killed pretty fast.  Use charm as a emergency option, and never try to charm anything if you have a pet already, it's just a uber-taunt, and a mana waster.  Despite all the negitive posts about Whirl Till You Hurl (VERY short duration) this is a really nice spell.  Not only does it root the target in place, it spins them around, and makes them unable to fight back, letting you do some extra daamage.  It dosn't last long (.5second to 10 seconds, i've noticed), but it's still pretty nice.  You need to get your butt over to highhold keep and get your pet spells from now on, your level 12 pet is a VERY good thing, it's your toughest yet, and will amaze you in battle time and again.  For getting to highpass, if you must do this alone, go in invis, don't mess with things.  Trains here are bad, and they tend to mob on you when you're after that single even kill.  Find someone that knows the area, and get them to get you inside the keep.  Female Eurodite, keep library, sells your pet spells.  If you can afford the PP, get your 16 and 20 while you are here too, save yourself a trip.<BR>
<BR>
I had a really tough time 14-16, honostally.  My DD was becoming quite laughable, and I just died, a lot.  NRO dervish camps started to yeild litle exp, and most things in Oasis could kill be pretty quick.  I did find hunting crocs with groups in oasis, and soloing the blue/even cons when I didn't have a group.  You finally have enough mana to really be making use of mezmorize, the dervish camps in NRO will really love to have you, as they watch you fix that nasty 3 pull and keep the dervishes drooling into you're ready for them.  WC is also good at this level, just a little risky alone.  The Orc camp in WC is usually open, unlike the EC orc camps, which are camped very often.  This is a really good camp for you, you can make a fine puller using your lull line of spells and tashan'ing a single pull from the middle of the full spawn.  This 12-16 takes time, so be patient.<BR>
<BR>
sixteen, in my opinion, is where you start getting some of the best things for this class.  Enter, the breeze spell.  This spell is ONLY available in Kunark, and I don't know your chances of getting there alone and buying the spell.  I know by this level you should have some friends that will do this for you.  If you don't, ask around, chances are you can get someone to do it for you for a few PP.  Breeze is your party's friend, speeds the mana regeneration of it's target, and you can make some serious PP casting this on people, it's a very usefull spell, and it's referred to as Crack, your targets will always be back for another hit.<BR>
<BR>
Sanity Warp comes into play, your 88-point DD spell.  This is a double edged-sword with this spell...It goes some great damage, and dosn't have a bad casting time.  Draw-backs:  This is a ultra-mega-uber taunt, and will pull the critter from most anything it wants to kill and come after you.  Be standing by at all times with your Rune spell, so you can take a hit or three and have the time to memory blur your target, and make it forget about how bad it hates you.  Sanity warp, i'm finding, gets a decent amount of resists, so use Tashan /always/ on those mobs that seem to resist this nice DD spell.  Quickness is a really nice spell, short duration, but increases your targets attack rate around 20%, keep this spell on your tanks, even your pet, sheesh, yourself if you plan on meeling, and you'll be hooked. Your new animation is very good, dealing double 20hits quite often, and taking a bit to kill.  Using all of your spells and abilities now, you should be a very wonderful addition to any group, breezing, casting quickness, mezzing those extra pulls, nuking things, casting rune on that puller or the person taking too many hits (I cannot count the number of times i've saved my or someone else's life by using this spell, when your healer is out of mana, you can keep someone alive for a bit.) The cost of rune is a bit, at 2gp a pop for the componot, but use it sparingly and don't advertise it too much, and the PP you're making for casting breeze and off loot will cover you well enough to where you should have a couple stacks of the stones ready for use.  Enchant Electum is also added, and now you start over, working the simple stones with the bars, and making some more powerful items that sell for quite a bit more. <BR>
<BR>
My enchanter has finally hit 17, and I'm in love with this character.  We have drawbacks, we can't deal out much DD, we can't take a hit, but we are enchanters -- we can enter the minds of our enemies and make them do things they would not normally do.  Killing solo is hard now, but you don't have to worry too much about things if you are learning how to use your pet and how to control that monster, at all costs.  I have a very hard time in dungeons right now, crushbone is still pretty dangerous to me, and i've found that our class is really designed for work in a group, which is fine with me, that's a lot of fun.<BR>
<BR>
Let me know if anyone needs any more advice, or if this was usefull in any way to anyone.<BR>
<BR>
17th Circle Enchantress<BR>
Lanis Ty'Ville server<BR>
<BR>
Cendorie
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
