	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Here are some good tips for enchanters:<BR>
<BR>
Move around! After you mez a creature, move to the opposite side of the party from the critter, but leave it targetted. If you are outdoors, move far enough away that you can re-mez before it gets to you. This does two things: since all the tanks are closer to the mez'd monster than you are, the odds are that it will jump one of them instead of you. So you can remez in peace. They may not be happy about it, but it is better for the monster to hit a tank for a round or two than for you to waste too much time remezing (you need to be watching for new adds).<BR>
<BR>
Mez-root-mez. Overlap mez and root when you get pulls large enough that mez's will break before your party has finished the main target. First mez everything, then, starting with the first thing you mez'd do tash, root, blur. Now everything is rooted and has forgotten about you and when your mez wears off it will be stuck in place for a while (root sticks pretty good after tash as long as nobody is damaging the target) allowing you to remez at your leisure.<BR>
<BR>
Debuff mez'd. Get your party trained to debuff mez'd creatures. Every creature you mez should get snare, slow and tash at least. <BR>
<BR>
Bad party? Use charm. If your party is not assisting I find the following routine works: <BR>
Step 1) explain things carefully. call a halt to pulling to do this. some people really don't know all this yet.<BR>
Step 2) withhold speed buffs--claim you are using so much mana mezzing and remezzing that your are too LOM to quickness.<BR>
Step 3) announce that you are removing mez from memory. (don't actually do this, you might want to save your own butt)<BR>
Step 4) if all else fails, you can use charm and root for CC. It's not as good, and I only reccomend doing this in blue groups, but it's not a total waste of time as this is what you will have to learn to do if you ever plan on fighting giants.<BR>
Step 5) /ooc Level ## Enchanter LFG<BR>
Step 6) parse all the tells inviting you and pick the party you want<BR>
<BR>
Learn to build groups. Yes, rangers are leaders, blah blah blah. But as an enchanter you will die ALOT in poorly designed parties. Keep a list of good pullers and healers from past parties. Once you know a zone, build your own party just how you want it. Then, since you have a good party and are an enchanter you can make a habit of going to the nastiest parts of a zone and banking big exps instead of huddling by the zone in safety and waiting for spawns.<BR>
<BR>
Teach casters to run to you when aggroed. First, this makes it easier for you to target the aggro monster and second you can protect them by dropping an AE stun. With an enchanter around the stupidest thing they can do is run OUT of your mez range.<BR>
<BR>
Outdoors, you are the secondary puller. If mana is good, learn to put wanderers on ice to kill so your party doesn't waste as much time waiting on the puller. This works really well once you get longer duration mez's.<BR>
<BR>
In small parties, charm is excellent at midhigh to high level. Just team up with one tank and one healer and have the tank two-pull. Charm the weaker willed of the two. This is a much more efficient use of your mana than DD and once your charisma gets good enough a charm will routinely last 3-4 fights. Just have the party ready to help when the charm breaks. If planned, they need to snare or root it. If charm breaks during a fight, just stun it and mez it.<BR>
<BR>
Just a few tips, YMMV<BR>
<BR>
Torgul<BR>
Enchanter - Prexus<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

